<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-018-204  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 018 204.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  Jan 1990 v7 n1 p13(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Reverse engineering and design recovery: a taxonomy. (definitionsof key terms in reverse engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Chikofsky, Elliot J.; Cross, James H. II.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Definitions of key terms related to software reverse engineeringare presented.andP;  'Reverse engineering' originally referred to thepractice of determining the specifications of complex hardware byexamining finished products.andP;  Hardware reverse-engineering seeksto duplicate a system; software reverse-engineering seeks tounderstand it in order to aid maintenance.andP;  A life-cycle modeldivides the life of a system into three phases: requirements,design, and implementation.andP;  Forward engineering moves fromhigh-level abstractions to physical implementation;re-documentation involves creating or revising equivalentrepresentations at the same abstraction level.andP;  Restructuringtransforms one form of representation to another, whilere-engineering is the modification of a subject system into a newform.andP;  The goals of reverse engineering include data recovery andcoping with complexity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TerminologyReverse EngineeringSoftware EngineeringProduct Life CycleSoftware ComplexityDocumentation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Relationship between terms. (chart)Models of tool architecture. (chart)Differences between viewpoints. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>